{
  "text": "Cystatin C levels are elevated with mild degrees of renal insufficiency, whereas serum creatinine levels are not. [CITATION_1] The metabolic abnormalities present in the early stages of kidney dysfunction are not the result of retained waste products or the failure to maintain the homeostasis of body fluids. These abnormalities are the result of the adaptations made to maintain the homeostasis. The circulating levels of parathyroid hormone are elevated in response to a normal intake of calcium and phosphorus. Sodium regulatory hormones like atrial natriuretic peptide are elevated in persons with unrestricted sodium intake. The capacity to buffer and excrete acid loads is reduced, and excess acid is buffered in tissues like bone. The clinical expression of these adaptive and abnormal processes is often delayed until a later stage of kidney dysfunction. However, in this study, we may be identifying complications (ie, cortical and posterior subcapsular cataracts) that occur in response to some metabolic factor during an early stage of kidney disease.",
  "citation_candidates": [
